can I call document.getElementById with # in front of the id?

No, when using `document.getElementById()`, you should not include the `#` symbol. The `#` is used in CSS selectors and `querySelector()`, but not in `getElementById()`.

Correct usage:
```javascript
// Correct
document.getElementById("myId");

// Incorrect
document.getElementById("#myId");  // Won't work
```

If you want to use the `#` selector syntax, you should use `querySelector()` instead:
```javascript
// This works
document.querySelector("#myId");
```

Both methods will find an element with `id="myId"`, but `getElementById()` expects just the ID name without any selector syntax.
