ok, so I recently refactored this to add support for anchor tags (the handlenavigation). however, i also need to keep support for the old pattern of creating a button with an ID that refers to slideover that will have id="${id}-container". I think the conflicting part here is that in handlenavigation we're calling the show method bound to the correct container element, but the trigger buttons are bound to `show` - ideally they only hold the ID to the container and show is always bound to the container - but i'm not sure how to do this.
I understand - you want to standardize the pattern so that `show` is always bound to the container element, regardless of whether it's triggered by a navigation event or a button click. Here's how you could modify the code:

```typescript
function createEventsForFragment(frag) {
  const triggerShowElements = frag.querySelectorAll('._slide-over-show-trigger');

  triggerShowElements.forEach(trigger => {
    trigger.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
      // Get the ID of the container from the trigger button
      const containerId = `${trigger.id}-container`;
      const container = document.getElementById(containerId);

      if (container) {
        show.call(container, event);
      }
    });
  });

  const triggerHideElements = frag.querySelectorAll('._slide-over-hide-trigger');
  triggerHideElements.forEach(element => {
    element.addEventListener('click', hide);
  });
}
```

This way, both patterns will work:
1. Clicking a button with ID "x" will look for and show the container with ID "x-container"
2. Using an anchor tag with href="#x" will directly show the container with ID "x"

The `show` function is always bound to the container element in both cases. This makes the behavior more consistent and easier to reason about.

You could even add a safety check in case someone forgets to add the "-container" suffix to their IDs:

```typescript
function createEventsForFragment(frag) {
  const triggerShowElements = frag.querySelectorAll('._slide-over-show-trigger');

  triggerShowElements.forEach(trigger => {
    trigger.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
      // Try with -container suffix first
      let container = document.getElementById(`${trigger.id}-container`);

      // If not found, try using the ID directly
      if (!container) {
        container = document.getElementById(trigger.id);
      }

      if (container) {
        show.call(container, event);
      } else {
        console.warn(`No slide-over container found for trigger: ${trigger.id}`);
      }
    });
  });

  // ... rest of the code
}
```

This makes the code more flexible while maintaining a consistent pattern of always binding `show` to the container element.
